Can the euro be fixed?
Paris—German Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble recently put the option of Greece's exit from the euro on the table, hoping to signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal prompted a broad discussion about the principles underlying the euro, its governance model, and the rationale for its existence.
Two weeks before Schäuble's proposal, European leaders had already noted the report on the future of the euro written by European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. But the new debate over Greece has led many policymakers to consider a return to the starting point.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they share a single currency.
Is this meaningful? About whether Greece can form a consensus on its future?
Currency is like a nation, and it needs myths to establish it.
Conventional wisdom holds that the euro was a political price Germany paid to France for reunification.
In fact, German reunification was just the final step of an engineering project in the late 1980s to solve a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, seeing them as incompatible with a single market; yet they were reluctant to maintain a currency regime dominated by the Bundesbank in the long term.
True European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
With hindsight, German reunification appears more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was locked in 1999, Germany was overvalued and its economy was difficult; France was undervalued and its economy was booming.
In the following decade, imbalances gradually emerged between the re-emerging Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And as the global financial crisis hit in 2008, these conditions became the perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
Would a fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Would the Deutsche Mark be overvalued again?
Would countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Would a housing bubble rise in Spain?
Will there be more or less government reform?
It is impossible to establish a reverse analysis baseline to evaluate the impact of the euro.
But this should not be a reason for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the eurozone economy has consistently underperformed, and its political institutions must take responsibility for this.
The real question is whether the common European currency remains important for the future.
This question is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginably high (and would be even higher if the break-up of the eurozone were to occur during a crisis and exacerbate the competition between participating countries).
In addition, abolishing the euro might unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
But, as Kevin O’Rourke recently pointed out at Oxford University, this view is not sufficient.
Logically, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should keep their marriage intact because the divorce costs too much.
Does the euro still make sense then?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
They assumed that a monetary union would promote economic integration and consolidate Europe's long-term growth.
Instead, intra-Eurozone trade and investment growth have been lackluster, while growth potential has actually diminished.
This is partly because national governments did not build on the currency union to turn the Eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead tried to retain their remaining powers.
This may make sense politically, but it is economically disastrous: Europe's huge internal market is one of its main assets, so there should be no opportunity wasted to strengthen it.
Secondly, people hope that the euro will become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and institutional requirements).
And according to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has largely been realized.
The euro's international use is second only to the US dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Thirdly, people (not without naivety) believe that the institutions underpinning the euro could improve the overall quality of economic policies, as if the level of policy at the European level is naturally higher than at the national level.
Following the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test came: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis while underestimating its financial dimension, resulting in worse performance compared to the US and the UK.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further policy reforms must be made.
But formulating and implementing a timetable for this requires broad agreement on the nature of the problems.
And ongoing debates over the Greek problem show that Europe is far from reaching consensus: participating countries have conflicting analyses of the roots of the debt crisis, leading to conflicting remedies.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University has observed that early efforts at international public health cooperation were hampered by different patterns of infectious disease transmission among countries.
Nations all favored joint action but could not agree on a cohesive plan because they differed on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone faces today.
Luckily, this problem is not unsolvable. Major reforms like establishing the European Stability Mechanism (European Stability Mechanism) and launching the banking union have shown that.
Inconsistencies have not prevented the ECB from taking decisive action, which indicates that institutional governance is indeed important.
But reforms and actions only began recently and were implemented under the pressure of a severe crisis, a fact that makes clear the difficulty in reaching consensus.
Europe cannot afford to delay or pretend anymore.
Eurozone member states must establish a consistent agenda on governance and political reforms to turn the monetary union into an engine of prosperity, or else they will sink into endless debate and crisis until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is the prerequisite for serious discussions and grand reforms.
Now, all major stakeholders have a duty to clearly articulate what they consider essential and what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to negotiate in exchange for what they want.
